# Build context = the repo root (see docker-compose.yml). Everything the images
# need is a package.json, a lockfile, a tsconfig, or a package's src/ + public/.
# Anything else only slows the build and, worse, risks leaking host state into an
# image layer.

# Never ship secrets. `.env` is the operator's live configuration and is handed to
# the containers at RUN time via `env_file:` in compose — it must never be baked in.
#
# `**/.env`, NOT `.env`. Docker matches these patterns against the whole
# context-relative path, so a bare `.env` excludes ONLY the root one. This repo also
# carries `packages/server/.env` (a local, gitignored dev config), and the
# `build-server` stage does `COPY packages/server ./packages/server` — so with the
# bare pattern that file, JWT/session secrets and all, was baked straight into the
# `bootstrap` image layer, recoverable by anyone who could pull it. Same reasoning as
# `**/logs` below.
**/.env
**/.env.*
!**/.env.example

# Host artefacts. `**/dist` matters for correctness, not just size: the images build
# every package from source, and a stale host build sneaking in could shadow it.
**/node_modules
**/dist
**/build
**/coverage
**/*.tsbuildinfo
# `**/logs`, NOT `logs`. Docker matches these patterns against the whole
# context-relative path, so a bare `logs` excludes ONLY the root logs/ — and
# `packages/server/logs/` (the rotating request/audit logs a developer's local
# `npm run dev` leaves behind, full of real IPs, user-agents and emails) would be
# copied straight into the shipped images. It also made the build depend on
# whether the developer happened to have that directory: its presence masked a
# hard failure in the bootstrap image (see docker/Dockerfile's bootstrap stage).
**/logs
dev-dist
test-results
playwright-report

# Not needed to build or run.
.git
.gitignore
.gitattributes
.github
.husky
.vscode
.idea
e2e
**/tests
# Depth-agnostic for the same reason as `**/.env`: a bare `*.md` / `*.tmp` would only
# ever match at the context root, letting a package-level README — or a stray `.tmp`
# backup left mid-edit — ride into an image layer.
**/*.md
**/*.tmp
